  1. (6pts) Repeat Part B, but this time, facet on the food group instead of coloring the points. In your opinion, is it easier to see food group-specific trends between fat and energy with facetting or with the colors? Do you think this is true generally, or does it depend on the problem?
ggplot(food, aes(x = fat_100g, y = energy_100g)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(pnns_groups_1 ~ .) +
  theme(strip.text = element_text(size = 12)) +
  labs(x = "Fat per 100 g", y = "Energy per 100 g",
       title = "Energy vs Fat per 100 g of Food, by Food Group",
       col = "Food Group")

In this case, it is easier to see the food group-specific trends between fat and energy per 100 g when faceting on food group than when coloring by food group. We have data on eight different food groups, and there are many observations with similar fat/energy combinations. When coloring by food group, observations from distinct food groups are stacked on top of each other, making it difficult to pick out the trend for any specific food group. When faceting by food group, we can clearly pick out the trend between fat and energy for one food group at a time. The choice to color or facet by group should be problem-specific. For instance, suppose we have data on a small number of well-separated groups. Then plotting all observations on a single set of axes and coloring by group would make it easier to compare trends across groups.

## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

The non-linear trend curve is not clearly a better fit than the linear model. These outliers pull the line down, so that the curve predicts energy levels below the observed energy levels for all other outliers with over 82 g of fat.

  1. (4 points) As discussed in lecture, we write lm(y~x, data = data) to fit a linear regression of y on x. Here, y is considered the outcome, and x is considered the covariate. (Within lm(), the data argument isn’t necessary if x and y are already defined outside of a dataset.)

In this part, define a variable, linReg, as a linear regression between fat_100g and energy_100g (where energy_100g is treated as the outcome). linReg = lm(energy_100g~fat_100g, data = food)

  1. (10pts) Now consider the following plot:
library(tidyverse)
ggplot(food, aes(x = fat_100g, y = energy_100g, color = additives_n)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

The above scatterplot displays a linear regression for two subsets of data: One where additives_n = "No" (the red line) and one where additives_n = "Yes" (the blue line). As discussed in class, each regression line can be described by an intercept and a slope.

Now, consider the following linear regression output:

summary(lm(energy_100g ~ fat_100g*additives_n, data = food))

This is the interactive regression model that’s being plotted above. Given this output, answer the following questions. For each question, briefly explain how you arrived at your answer.

For this part, it can be helpful to write out the prediction equation that’s being produced in the above output:

\[\widehat{\text{energy}} = \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_F \cdot \text{fat} + \hat{\beta}_A \cdot I_A + \hat{\beta}_{FA} \cdot \text{fat} \cdot I_A\]

where \(I_A = 1\) if a food has additives_n = "Yes" and \(I_F = 0\) if a food has additives_n = "No". Given the above, we can write out the prediction equation for foods with and without additives:

  • Additives: \(\widehat{\text{energy}} = \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_F \cdot \text{fat} + \hat{\beta}_A + \hat{\beta}_{FA} \cdot \text{fat} = (\hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_A) + (\hat{\beta}_F + \hat{\beta}_{FA}) \cdot \text{fat}\)

  • No Additives: \(\widehat{\text{energy}} = \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_F \cdot \text{fat}\)

Given this, and the output above (which gives us estimates for all four \(\beta\) parameters), we can quickly answer the following questions:

  • For additives_n = "No" foods (i.e., the red regression line), what is the estimated intercept?

The estimated intercept is \(\hat{\beta}_0 = 578.4644\).

  • For additives_n = "No" foods (i.e., the red regression line), what is the estimated slope?

The estimated slope is \(\hat{\beta}_F = 33.5129\).

  • For additives_n = "Yes" foods (i.e., the red regression line), what is the estimated intercept?

The estimated intercept is \(\hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_A = 578.4644 + 78.1142 = 656.5786\).

  • For additives_n = "Yes" foods (i.e., the red regression line), what is the estimated slope?

The estimated slope is \(\hat{\beta}_F + \hat{\beta}_{FA} = 33.5129 + 6.9130 = 40.4259\).

Note: This question might be tricky if you haven’t seen linear regression before, so please ask us for help if you’re confused here!

  1. (5pts) Given the regression output in Part C, answer the following:

Using the prediction equation we wrote out in the previous part, we can plug in values for fat_100g and additives_n to answer the following questions.

  • What is the estimated mean energy_100g when fat_100g = 100 and additives_n = "No"?

\(578.4644 + 100 \cdot 33.5129 = 3929.754\)

  • What is the estimated mean energy_100g when fat_100g = 100 and additives_n = "Yes"?

These questions basically boil down to: What are the right endpoints of the red and blue lines in the plot? However, you should be able to compute exact numbers for this question.

  1. (5pts) In the output in Part C, you should see that the term fat_100g:additives_nYes has a positive estimate (6.9130) and a very small p-value. In 1-2 sentences, answer the following: What is your interpretation of this finding, within the context of the graph in Part C?

The coefficient for fat_100g:additives_nYes corresponds to the change in slope between foods without additives (additives_n = "No") and foods with additives (additives_n = "Yes"). From the output, we see that this estimated change is positive and statistically significant, in the sense that we reject the null hypothesis that this population-level mean change in slopes is equal to 0. Thus, we can interpret this finding as: The slope of the blue line is steeper than the slope of the red line, to a statistically significant degree.

Problem 3: Plotting Subsets of Data (15 points)

Often we want to focus our graphs and analyses on particular subsets of the data - this has already come up a few times in the class. To get particular subsets of data in R, the function subset is very useful. I’ve actually used the subset() function a fair number of times already in this class (in labs/homeworks).

Using the subset function, create two datasets: sugary, which contains foods whose food group is “Sugary snacks”, and cerealPotato, which contains foods whose food group is “Cereals and potatoes”. (No, I don’t know why these people lumped cereals and potatoes together.) Then, for each of these subsets, create a scatterplot with fat_100g on the x-axis and energy_100g on the y-axis, and add a nonlinear trend line ("loess") to each of these plots (no standard errors added).

In 1-2 sentences, compare and contrast the trend lines you see.

The following code creates the datasets sugary and cerealPotato, which contain only “Sugar snacks” and “Cereals and potatoes”, respectively.

sugary = subset(food, pnns_groups_1 == "Sugary snacks")
cerealPotato = subset(food, pnns_groups_1 == "Cereals and potatoes")

Then, we can create a scatterplot for each of these datasets, with a nonlinear trend added to each plot:

library(gridExtra)
sugarPlot = ggplot(sugary, aes(x = fat_100g, y = energy_100g)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE) +
  labs(x = "Fat per 100 g", y = "Energy per 100 g", 
       title = "Energy vs Fat per 100 g \n for Sugary Snacks")
cpPlot = ggplot(cerealPotato, aes(x = fat_100g, y = energy_100g)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE) +
  labs(x = "Fat per 100 g", y = "Energy per 100 g", 
       title = "Energy vs Fat per 100 g \n for Cereals/Potatoes")
grid.arrange(sugarPlot, cpPlot, nrow = 1)

A few observations can be made from the above plots. First, by comparing the y-axes, we can see that sugary snacks tend to have more energy (in terms of calories) than the cereals-and-potatoes dataset. After accounting for this difference, it appears that the trends for both datasets are quite similar. For the cereals-and-potatoes dataset, we can see that there is a bit more fluctuation in this trend - this is because there is (compared to the sugary snacks dataset) a lot more variation in energy_100g (this makes sense, because the cereals-and-potatoes subset probably contains a more heterogeneous set of foods than the sugary snacks subset).
